<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hubbard's Remarks on South's `NSL' Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0403050294 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0437 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0403050294 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["U.S. State Department Reaffirms Demand for Abolition of </F>
`NSL' in S. Korea" -- KCNA headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, March 4 (KCNA) -- The U.S. State 
Department reportedly reaffirmed Wednesday that the demand for 
the abolition of the "National Security Law" in South Korea was 
the official stand of the United States. 
  Commenting on the great sensation in South Korea caused by 
the remarks of Deputy Assistant Secretary of State Hubbard 
urging the abrogation of the "NSL" in South Korea, its spokesman 
declared again what this senior U.S. Government official had 
said was not his personal view and what the United States 
demanded was not the revision of the "NSL" but its abolition. 
  Noting that the maintenance of the "NSL" was illogical, the 
State Department said what the United States demanded of South 
Korea was the abrogation of the "NSL" and this was the U.S. 
official stand. 
  This statement of the U.S. State Department came at a time 
when the South Korean puppet Foreign Ministry authorities met 
officials of the U.S. Embassy in Seoul and asked them to inform 
the U.S. Government of the sensation created in South Korea by 
the remarks of the deputy assistant secretary of state. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

