<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government `Regrets' U.S. Super 301 Revival </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0403011294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0105 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0403011294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 4 (YONHAP) -- South Korea has protested 
the United States' decision to revive the Super 301 trade 
provision, demanding that Washington adhere to world trade rules 
rather than resorting to unilateral action. 
  "The South Korean Government regrets that the U.S. 
administration decided to revive the Super 301 provision on 
March 3, at a point when the Uruguay Round multilateral trade 
talks had been concluded after seven years of negotiations and 
when the world trade organization is to be formally launched 
from 1995 after an official signing next month," a Foreign 
Ministry spokesman said. 
  The spokesman reminded that Seoul had repeatedly stressed in 
South Korean-U.S. economic talks that trade disputes should not 
be dealt with through the domestic procedures of any single 
nation. 
  Seoul re-emphasizes its belief that disputes "should be 
resolved through the strengthened and supplemented settlement 
procedures of the world trade organization," the spokesman said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

