<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official on Effect of `Super 301' Revival </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0403082394 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0704 GMT 4 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0403082394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Ministry of Trade, Industry, and Energy today 
pointed out that the U.S. revival of the Super 301 trade 
provision conflicts [ogunnanun kosirago] with the Uruguay Round 
spirit and expressed concern that the U.S. action may hamper 
[chohae] the newly established world free trade order. 
  Urging the United States to exercise control in invoking the 
Super 301 clause of its own volition [chauijogin supo 301 
paltongul chaje], Han Yong-su, director of the ministry's Trade 
Cooperation Division, said: I do not think the U.S. action will 
immediately effect ROK-U.S. trade relations fundamentally 
[kunbonjogin] because ROK-U.S. trade is currently fairly 
[pigyojok] balanced and because the two countries are headed 
towards resolving matters of mutual interest through 
consultation channels. 
  Director Han said: If the United States takes action 
regarding the ROK, we will solve problems that arise from U.S. 
actions according to dispute-settlement procedures of the 
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade and the World Trade 
Organization. 
  He also said: The government will utilize various channels 
to prevent incorrect or false information on the ROK from making 
its way into the annual U.S. report on each country's trade 
barriers. At the same time, it will support active dialogue 
between ROK and U.S. businessmen through ROK-U.S. industrial 
cooperation channels in nine areas which include the computer 
and semiconductor sectors. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

