<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Firm Plans Direct Inter-Korean Sea Route </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0403034294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0204 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0403034294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 4 (YONHAP) -- A shipping firm in 
Yanbian autonomous district for ethnic Koreans in northeast 
China is promoting plans to open a direct sea route between 
North and South Korea, business sources said on Thursday. 
  Yanbian Shipping Co. is negotiating with the South Korean 
Government via its Seoul agent, Korea Special Shipping Co., 
about its plans to have a 499-ton container ship sail between 
South Korea's Pusan and North Korea's Chongjin once a week. 
  Foreign ships operating irregularly between North and South 
Korea now carry goods as there is no regular shipping service 
linking the two. 
  If the route is opened, the Chinese shipping firm will use 
it 
to transport goods chiefly between South Korea and Yanbian, 
rather than between the two Koreas, as there are rail links 
between Chongjin and Yanbian, the sources said. 
  An official of the Korea Maritime and Port Administration 
said his office had not yet received an application for opening 
a sea route between Pusan and Chongjin from the shipper. 
  "When we receive the application, we'll decide on it after 
consulting with related government ministries," he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

