<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Comforts Families of Crash Victims </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0403070694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0532 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0403070694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 4 (YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam on 
Friday morning visited a military hospital where the bodies of 
Air Force Chief of Staff Gen. Cho Kun-hae, his wife and four 
others killed in a helicopter crash on Thursday lay in state, 
offering condolences to their bereaved families. He was 
accompanied by Defense Minister Yi Pyong-tae and Chief 
Presidential Secretary Pak Kwan-yong. 
  Kim told Air Force Vice Chief of Staff Lt. Gen. Choe 
Tong-hwan and other Air Force leaders to make thorough 
preparations for the victims' funerals, which the government 
will hold as an Air Force rite. The Ministry of Patriots and 
Veterans Affairs has decided to pay the victims' bereaved 
families compensation totaling 280 million won (350,000 U.S. 
dollars). 
  Gen. Cho's family will receive 109 million won, Maj. Kang 
Song-yun's (pilot) 51 million won, Capt. Yu Yong-chae's 
(co-pilot) 34 million won, Capt. Yi Sang-hun's (Gen. Cho's aide) 
40 million won and Msgt. Chon Hae-won's (navigator) 46 million 
won. The government will honor them all, providing a decoration 
for Gen. Cho and special promotions for the other. 
  Meanwhile, an Air Force team investigating the crash found 
the helicopter's voice recorder late Thursday night and turned 
it over to the National Scientific Investigation Institute for 
closer examination. Partially damaged, the recorder contains 
taped communications between the pilot and the flight control 
officer, which is expected to reveal the cause of the crash. 
  The Air Force is considering two reasons for the crash: 
Engine failure due to poor maintenance and the pilot's failure 
to cope with a sudden weather change. 

</TEXT>

