<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Car Sales in UK Not Hurt </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0303134994 Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES in English 2 Mar 
94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> BK0303134994 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, Tues -- The National Automobile 
Manufacturing Industry Limited is confident the government's 
decision to deny new contracts to British firms will not 
influence its customers in the United Kingdom. Its public 
relations manager, Nik Kamariah Nik Abdul Rahman, said today 
Proton's [Malaysian car] involvement in the United Kingdom 
market was solely a business venture. 
  The Proton cars have received strong response in the country 
because of their quality and value coupled with the aggressive 
marketing strategy adopted by the distributor, Proton Cars (UK) 
Limited. She said Proton would countinue to support its 
distributor's commitment on services and warranty. 
  Proton has exported 70,491 cars to the United Kingdom since 
1989. The company expects to export 17,580 units this year. It 
was reported today Proton cars (UK) had told its customers and 
buyers not to be unduly concerned over the Malaysian 
Government's decision to stop awarding new contracts to British 
companies. 

</TEXT>

