<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sihanouk on Travel Plans, Impact of Illness </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0403111494 Phnom Penh REAKSMEI KAMPUCHEA in Cambodian 3 
Mar 94 pp 1, 2 </F>

<F P=103> BK0403111494 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh REAKSMEI KAMPUCHEA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Cambodian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] According to sources in Tokyo, in a message sent 
from Beijing, His Majesty King Norodom Sihanouk says that he 
will return to Phnom Penh on 8 April, six days before Cambodia's 
traditional new year, although he has to continue his medical 
treatment. After his arrival in Phnom Penh the king will 
organize a ceremony to mark the 90th anniversary of his late 
mother, Queen Sisowath Kosomak, to be held in the royal palace 
one day after his arrival. 
  In this message the king says that he plans to meet with 
Cambodian Government leaders and the Throne Council. Apart from 
this, the king will remain in Cambodia in order to receive 
credentials from various ambassadors, who were recently 
appointed, such as the envoy from Great Britain. 
  The king will also stay on to take part in the new year 
celebrations, a tradition of the Cambodian nation. Apart from 
this, the prince father will also receive an important guest. 
This is the state visit by the prime minister of Malaysia, who 
will shortly visit Cambodia. [passage omitted] 
  Before returning to Phnom Penh in early April, the king will 
leave Beijing for Pyongyang, North Korea, for a three- or 
four-day visit and then leave from there for Phnom Penh. 
  The king, however, says that Chinese doctors have asked him 
to return to Beijing in June to continue his medical treatment. 
The king notes that: "I am a lot better from the cancer in the 
bone marrow in my back." I am far from being cured as concerns 
the cancerous marrow bone in my back. [preceding sentence in 
English] 
  King Norodom Sihanouk specifies that he can no longer 
continue his writing or his other literary activities because "I 
have become an old man who is sick, weak, and very fragile." It 
is to be noted that King Norodom Sihanouk underlines the words 
very fragile [preceding two words in English]. 
  The essence of this message was excerpted and printed in the 
CAMBODIA DAILY BULLETIN published in Phnom Penh in three 
languages. This bulletin also reveals that a palace official in 
Phnom Penh affirmed on 28 February that the king plans to return 
to Phnom Penh on 8 April. This official, however, did not give 
a schedule of King Norodom Sihanouk's visit to Pyongyang. He 
only said that "it is a tradition for the king to travel to 
Pyongyang close to 15 April, a date which coincides with the 
birthday of Kim Il-song." 

</TEXT>

