<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israelis To Consult on Water, Farm Projects </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0403034494 Bangkok THE NATION in English 4 Mar 94 p A7 </F>
<F P=103> BK0403034494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok THE NATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Israel will send experts to help the Thai 
government solve the water crisis, Deputy Prime Minister 
Suphachai Phanitchaphak said yesterday. Speaking about his 
recent trip to Israel, Suphachai said he had met with a water 
management consultancy which had agreed to dispatch a specialist 
team to find solutions to the worsening water shortage in 
Thailand. 
  He said that the company was the same one which came to 
Thailand 7-8 years ago. But its operations stopped when the 
World Bank withdrew financial support for the programme. 
Suphachai said he also asked the Israeli government to help 
Thailand in agriculture, especially technology on planting crops 
in salty areas. "I proposed that each project should be separate 
from others. For example, the Chao Phya River project is one 
project and the Nan River another," he said. 
  Supachai said the cost of Israel's assistance would be based 
on a flexible credit system. "It is likely there will be trade 
between the two countries in the future," he said. Supachai also 
said he had discussed increasing exports to Israel since "The 
private sector in Israel is also interested in the proposed 
cooperation," he said. 

</TEXT>

