<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Suphachai Views Trade Markets, Israeli Role </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0403062494 Bangkok PHUCHATKAN in Thai 4 Mar 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> BK0403062494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok PHUCHATKAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Thai </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Deputy Prime Minister Suphachai Phanitchaphak, in 
his capacity as chairman of the International Competitiveness 
Enhancing Committee, disclosed that during its meeting yesterday 
the committee reviewed the first chapter of the Industry 
Ministry's white paper on Thailand's competitors and their trade 
and marketing strategies. 
  Suphachai quoted the white paper as saying that China, 
Indonesia, Mexico, and Korea are Thailand's major trade 
competitors. Thailand has not yet lost its market share to these 
countries, however, but certainly will in the future if it 
remains idle and makes no further improvement. 
  The meeting also discussed potential markets for Thai 
products and Thailand's dominance in different markets. 
  Suphachai talked about his recent visit to Israel and 
several 
issues that were discussed, particularly bilateral cooperation 
in third country markets. At present, Israel is the only 
country which has received trade privileges from the United 
States, the European Union, and NAFTA. Suphachai said: "Israel 
can send its goods to these markets without having to comply 
with the quota system or facing tax barriers. For this reason, 
Thailand will try to send its goods to those markets through 
Israel. By so doing, the prices of Thai exports will have to be 
increased by 35 percent." 

</TEXT>

