<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Decree Allows Aliens To Work in Fish Industry </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0403034894 Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 4 Mar 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> BK0403034894 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BANGKOK POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A royal decree has been issued to allow aliens to 
work in the fishing industry to ease labour shortages, Deputy 
Labour and Social Welfare Minister Soemsak Karun said. He said 
the Government had also issued an order specifying steps and 
regulations in granting bail to foreigners who illegally enter 
Thailand to work in the fishing industry. The amount of bail 
has been reduced from 50,000 baht to 5,000 baht. 
  A number of Burmese have been hired to work in fishing 
industry, mining and construction. But most of them are illegal 
immigrants. 
  Mr Soemsak's remarks were made during the opening of a 
two-day seminar called "Problems and Ways to Solve the Labour 
Problem and Development in the Five Southernmost Provinces." 
The seminar ends today. 
  The seminar, attended by state and private officials at a 
meeting room of Yala Rama Hotel in Muang District, aims to find 
solutions to labour problems in Narathiwat, Pattani, Yala, 
Songkhla, and Satun. 
  The deputy labour minister said the Government and other 
state agencies concerned would try to upgrade the skills of Thai 
workers so that they could gain higher income. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

