<F P=100> AUSTRALASIA </F>
<F P=101> Australia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Turkish Foreign Minister Arrives on Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Calls on West To Press Serbs </H4>
<F P=102> NC0303191494 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1118 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0303191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Canberra, Mar. 3 (A.A.) -- Foreign Minister 
Hikmet Cetin said that as long as the west continues putting 
pressure on teh Serbians, peace in Bosnia-Herzegovina will be 
established soon. After concluding his three-day official visit 
to New Zealand, Cetin arrived in Australia on Wednesday. 
  Speaking to the press on the situation in the Balkans, Cetin 
said that any decision which was not based on political will and 
power will not be effective. He said that NATO and the U.N. 
Security Council should clearly give an ultimatum that further 
aggressions will not be tolerated. "The Bosnian tragedy showed 
that unless there is a power behind your decisions, no one will 
listen to you," he said. "Now, a new world disorder prevails in 
our region, instead of a new world order." Cetin stressed that 
Europe had failed to maintain peace in the Balkans. "The 
agreement reached between the Croats and Bosnians is an 
indication which gives us hope," he said. "A solution seems to 
be very near if the world applies pressure." 
  Cetin and his Australian counterpart Gareth Evans held 
official talks afterward. An extradition agreement was signed 
at the end of the talks. Cetin was received by Australian 
governor Bill Hayden and Prime Minister Paul Keating. Evans 
hosted a dinner for Cetin in the evening. Cetin was welcomed 
with a ceremony befitting heads of states, in Australia. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

