<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK, Japanese, Chinese, Russian Collegians Meet </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2202002794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0016 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2202002794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 22 (YONHAP) -- Over 40 collegians from 
South Korea, Japan, China and Russia have gathered in Seoul from 
Tuesday to March 3 to promote regional camaraderie. 
  The gathering is the second of its kind, with the first held 
in Tokyo last year, and is sponsored by the Foreign Ministry. 
The idea was proposed by former Japanese Prime Minister Kiichi 
Miyazawa and is expected to become an annual event. The aim of 
the gathering is to establish future-oriented relationships 
among four nations that were less than friendly during the Cold 
War era. 
  Participants will tour the National Assembly, the ancient 
Korean capital city of Kyongju, the truce village of Panmunjom 
and industrial sites. They will stay two nights at private 
homes to get acquainted with South Korean customs. 

</TEXT>

