<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government, Papers React to Super 301 Revival </TI></H3>
<H4>   Trade Ministry Issues Statement </H4>
<F P=102> SK0503024594 Seoul CHOSON ILBO in Korean 5 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> SK0503024594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul CHOSON ILBO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Kim Kwang-hyon] </F>
  [Text] The Ministry of Trade, Industry, and Energy [MTIE] 
on 4 March issued a statement reporting: "If the United States 
seeks to impose Super 301 trade-sanctions on the ROK, the ROK 
intends to refer the issue to the World Trade Organization 
[WTO], which is slated to begin in 1995 for the settlement of 
disputes." 
  In the statement entitled "the MTIE's position on the 
revival 
of Super 301 authority on trade-sanctions," Kim Chol-su, 
minister of Trade, Industry, and Energy, said: "The MTIE calls 
on the United States to restrain from invoking the authority 
arbitrarily [chauijogin]." 
  The minister also warned that: "The reinstatement of the 
Super 301 provision runs counter to the spirit of Uruguay Round, 
which concluded at the end of last year. We express concern 
that this may hinder the world's free trade order at a time when 
the WTO is about to begin." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

