<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hubbard Says Security Law Not on U.S. Agenda </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0503031294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0303 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0503031294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 5 (YONHAP) -- The U.S. official who 
commented earlier that Washington wants South Korea to repeal 
its National Security Law, said the United States does not 
intend to raise the issue at a bilateral level, the Foreign 
Ministry said Saturday. 
  Deputy Assistant Secretary of State Tom Hubbard held himself 
personally responsible for the ill-timed and misworded comments 
on the South Korean security law, admitting that he was not the 
appropriate person to make such remarks, Ministry officials said. 
  An official from the South Korean Embassy in Washington met 
with Hubbard and was told the United States does not plan to 
raise the issue as part of the bilateral agenda, they said. 
  "We believe that Mr. Hubbard made these remarks in his 
capacity as deputy secretary of state," one official said. 
  Hubbard told a seminar on Feb. 25 that the United States 
hopes South Korea will abolish its National Security Law, which 
bars any unauthorized contact with North Korea or any activities 
sympathetic to the communist regime. 
  The remarks came under immediate fire as unwelcome 
interference in Seoul's internal affairs. Hubbard drew even 
more criticism because he was chief U.S. working-level delegate 
to nuclear negotiations with North Korea. 
  At the meeting with South Korean Embassy official, Hubbard 
reasserted that his statements were in line with Washington's 
1993 human rights report, which said the South Korean law is 
subject to abuse. 
  Admitting his personal responsibility, Hubbard said he 
should 
not have made such comments in light of his capacity as chief 
negotiator with Pyongyang on nuclear affairs, officials said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-5216 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas044_d_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-044 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks With U.S. Expected After IAEA Inspection </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0503030694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0252 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0503030694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 5 (YONHAP) -- South Korea and the 
United States will discuss the North Korean nuclear situation 
next week to map out future steps after International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA) inspections are concluded. 
  Assistant Secretary of State Robert Gallucci, chief U.S. 
nuclear negotiator with North Korea, will come to Seoul on 
March 10 and meet with several South Korean officials the 
following two days to coordinate a bilateral stance. 
  Gallucci will likely be accompanied by David Brown, chief of 
the Korea desk at the State Department, and Gary Samore, deputy 
chief in charge of non-proliferation. 
  Tom Hubbard, the top U.S. representative at working-level 
negotiations with Pyongyang, is unable to accompany the 
delegation because he is acting as assistant secretary in lieu 
of Winston Lord, who is on a trip to Asia. 
  Seoul and Washington will draw up measures expected after 
the 
IAEA team, currently in the middle of inspections, successfully 
concludes its monitoring of Pyongyang's nuclear facilities in 
another week or so. They will discuss the agenda and principles 
for the next round of North Korea-U.S. high-level talks, set 
for March 21 in Geneva. 
  A key point concerns their demand for an inter-Korean 
presidential envoy exchange before the high-level talks can open. 
  North Korea has yet to indicate that it will meet this 
demand. Seoul and Washington are expected to reconfirm their 
position that substantive inter-Korean dialogue is a condition 
for the March 21 meeting. 
  Gallucci plans to hold a press conference on March 12 and 
leave the following day. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

