<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Inter-Korean Summit Talks `Likely' in Beijing </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0603034294 Seoul CHOSON ILBO in Korean 6 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> SK0603034294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul CHOSON ILBO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] North Korean President Kim Il-song is expected to 
visit China during ROK President Kim Yong-sam's visit to China 
scheduled for 26 March, sources in Beijing said on 5 March. The 
sources reported that the Chinese side, therefore, is very 
likely to arrange inter-Korean summit talks in Beijing, adding 
that China has secretly pushed ahead with these arrangements. 
  The sources said that it was part of this plan that Li 
Shuzheng, head of the International Liaison Department of the 
Communist Party of China, visited Pyongyang on 24 February, met 
Kim Il-song, and delivered an invitation to visit China in the 
name of Jiang Zemin, CPC general secretary and Chinese president. 
  Meanwhile, a ROK Government source on 5 March reported: "It 
seems true that China invited President Kim Il-song to visit 
China, but there is no possibility of inter-Korean summit talks 
being held in China." 
  The source added: "We understand that China invited 
President Kim Il-song to visit in April. Therefore, the summit 
talks are impossible due to the timing. Even if the two 
presidents were to visit Beijing at the same time, inter-Korean 
summit talks in Beijing would be an awkward arrangement in view 
of the nature of the talks." 

</TEXT>

