<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Rules Out Summit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0703030894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0303 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0703030894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 7 (YONHAP) -- Presidential spokesman 
Chu Ton-sik on Monday denied foreign press reports that an 
inter-Korean summit meeting may be held in Beijing when South 
Korean President Kim Yong-sam visits the Chinese capital in late 
March. 
  "There is no possibility of a South-North summit in Beijing 
during President Kim Yong-sam's visit to China," Chu said. 
  "An inter-Korean summit is not such a simple matter as to be 
realized just because the two leaders are visiting Beijing 
nearly at the same time," Chu said. 
  In order for Seoul and Pyongyang to hold a summit, extensive 
consultations and preparations must take place, Chu said. At 
present, there is no possibility that Presidents Kim Yong-sam 
and Kim Il-song will visit Beijing at the same time, Chu added. 
  Reliable sources in Beijing said Monday that the North 
Korean 
president would visit China in May at the latest. 

</TEXT>

