<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Unification Minister on 9 Mar N-S Contact </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0503005694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0039 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0503005694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 5 (YONHAP) -- South Korean Deputy Prime 
Minister Yi Yong-tok voiced confidence Saturday that North Korea 
would eventually agree to exchange special envoys, possibly 
before the Pyongyang-Washington high-level meeting on March 21, 
because it knows the exchange is a must for the talks with the 
United States. 
  In an interview with Japan's YOMIURI SHIMBUN, Yi, 
concurrently national unification board minister, said the 
Seoul-Pyongyang summit proposed by President Kim Yong-sam is 
possible anytime once the exchange is realized, hinting that 
South Korea is making necessary preparations. 
  If North Korea does not meet one of the prerequisites to a 
third-level meeting set by the United States -- full 
implementation of International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) 
inspections and an inter-Korean exchange of special envoys -- it 
will have difficulty realizing the March 21 talks in Geneva, Yi 
said. 
  Seoul and Washington have agreed to put off the March 21 
meeting if Pyongyang fails to meet the two conditions, he added. 
  "It is hard to predict the North's attitude," Yi said, 
commenting on the collapse of inter-Korean working-level 
dialogue on Thursday. "But we expect great progress on March 
9," he said. South and North Korea, without attaining tangible 
results on Thursday, agreed in principle to the envoy exchange 
and to meet next week for further discussions. He reiterated 
that Seoul wants to see visits by president-designated envoys 
from each side take place before March 21. 

</TEXT>

