<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Rejects 4 Mar Remarks on Envoy Exchange </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0503035394 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0300 GMT 5 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0503035394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In connection with the press statement by Kang 
Sok-chu, North Korean vice foreign minister, that the exchange 
of special envoys is not a precondition for the third round of 
the U.S.-North Korean talks, a senior government official today 
stressed that the government position that the exchange should 
be made before the third round of U.S.-North Korean talks 
remains unchanged. 
  The official said that although North Korea seems to be 
making this assertion on the basis that the exchange of special 
envoys was not specified in the U.S.-North Korean written 
agreement in New York, the exchange of special envoys was agreed 
upon internally between the United States and North Korea, 
though the United States acceded to the North Korean demand not 
to include it in the written agreement. 
  The official said that, therefore, Kang Sok-chu's allegation 
that the text of the New York agreement mentions only the 
resumption of the working contact and that it does not make any 
reference to the realization of the exchange of special envoys 
is an absurd allegation aimed at overturning the explicit 
agreement between the United States and North Korea. 

</TEXT>

