<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Investigating DPRK Arms Found in DMZ </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0703020194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0156 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0703020194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paju, March 7 (YONHAP) -- Military and police teams 
investigating weapons found along the Imjin River in the western 
section of the Demilitarized Zone [DMZ] on Sunday morning said 
the arms must have been left behind by a North Korean Army 
patrol trying to infiltrate one or two years ago. 
  Estimating the patrol consisted of around three soldiers 
from 
the Reconnaissance Battalion of the Second North Korean Army 
Corps, they said a rust-covered M-16 rifle and ammunition 
indicate the weapons had been there for one or two years. 
  The North Koreans probably disguised themselves as South 
Korean Army soldiers and tried to cross the river to observe 
construction of a freeway along its southern bank, which was 
completed more than a year ago, they observed. 
  The weapons, including a .66-caliber Soviet pistol with 17 
North Korean-made ammunition rounds, German binoculars, an M-16 
rifle with 213 rounds and two hand grenades, were found by Yi 
Hui-un, 35, of Munsan, Paju-gun, Kyonggi Province, and two 
friends along the river at 8:00 A.M. Sunday. 

</TEXT>

