<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Experiments in Land Cultivation Rights </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0603063094 Seoul CHOSON ILBO in Korean 6 Mar 94 p 11 </F>
<F P=103> SK0603063094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul CHOSON ILBO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by reporter Kim Chae-ho] </F>
  [Text] It has been confirmed that North Korea is 
experimenting with privatizing cultivation rights for farmland 
in limited areas. 
  Relevant government authorities in charge of North Korean 
economic affairs on 5 March said: Since the second half of 
1993, North Korea has been instituting, on a trial basis, a 
system for privatizing land cultivation rights for farmers in 
certain areas by which the North Korean authorities take a 
certain proportion of the harvested farm produce as a fee for 
the land and the farmers privately own the remainder of the farm 
produce. 
  The government official in charge of North Korean economic 
affairs said the government authorities have recently learned 
that North Korea has been secretly instituting this experimental 
reform measure in areas such as Hoeryong in North Hamgyong 
Province, where the residents are mostly political prisoners. 
North Korea is instituting this measure secretively on a family 
basis and is thoroughly cutting off the areas from the outside. 
The government official said: "North Korea seems to be 
experimenting on capitalist market economy principles by partly 
permitting cultivation rights and maintaining the present North 
Korean system to solve its serious food shortage problem." The 
official added, "North Korea selected the areas where political 
prisoners live for the experiment in order to closely study the 
possible effect of the change on the maintenance of the present 
North Korean system through the people most critical of the 
present North Korean system." 
  Another expert on North Korean affairs commented: "This is a 
significant change as it represents signs of a North Korean 
experiment on new land reform for the first time in 36 years 
since private ownership and land cultivation rights disappeared 
in North Korea in 1958." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

