<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japan's Hosokawa Calls President on Reforms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0703103094 Seoul YONHAP in English 1022 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0703103094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Mar. 7 (YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam 
received a telephone call from Japanese Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa on Monday afternoon, during which the Japanese premier 
congratulated the president on the recent passage of political 
reform bills through the National Assembly. 
  Chongwadae [presidential offices] spokesman Chu Ton-sik said 
that in the telephone conversation that lasted about 10 minutes 
from 5:10 P.M., Prime Minister Hosokawa said he was extending 
deep respect to President Kim for the leadership and 
determination he displayed before the passage of the bills. 
President Kim said to Hosokawa he had emphasized on every 
opportunities that no national advancement can be attained 
without political reforms. 
  The spokesman said the president also expressed the hope 
that 
current trade frictions between Japan and the United States will 
be resolved in an instructive direction. Hosokawa, according to 
Chu, said that the two countries have diverse problems of their 
own and he would like to exchange opinions on these issues with 
President Kim during his upcoming visit to Japan. 
  This was the fourth telephone conversation between Kim and 
Hosokawa since President Kim called the Japanese premier on last 
Aug. 9 to congratulate him on his inauguration. 

</TEXT>

