<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peacekeeping Unit in Somalia To Return 17 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0703080594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0746 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0703080594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 7 (YONHAP) -- The South Korean 
peacekeepers in Somalia will withdraw about one month ahead of 
the recently revised schedule and return home next week, the 
Foreign Ministry said Monday. The 250-man "Evergreen" Unit will 
leave the African country aboard a chartered plane on March 17 
and arrive in Seoul the following day, according to the 
ministry. The unit's equipment will arrive via ship and reach 
the port city of Pusan sometime next month. 
  The Evergreen Unit marked South Korea's first participation 
ever in a U.N. Peacekeeping Operation (PKO). It was dispatched 
to the strife-torn nation last July for a one-year tour of duty, 
but the Seoul government decided on an early withdrawal, around 
April, after scores of Western nations announced their intention 
to pull out. South Korea pushed up the withdrawal date to next 
week after similar decisions were made by the United States and 
other nations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

