<F P=104>  Seoul THE KOREA HERALD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The government yesterday dismissed Kyonggi 
provincial Gov. Yun Se-tal over the recent scandal surrounding 
the misappropriation of public donations to charity by officials 
at some countries under his control. 
  Yi Kyong-ho, assistant minister of home affairs, will be 
named new Kyonggi governor, a government spokesman said. 
  The government also sacked O Song-su, Songnam City mayor who 
is being dismissed for his "problematic" wealth accumulation, 
and Kim Hak-kyu, Hwasong County chief, with regard to the 
charity scandal, the official said. 
  Ha Yong-su, director-general of transportation and tourism 
affairs at Kyonggi provincial government, will receive 
disciplinary measures, according to the spokesman. 
  The dismissals came after the Home Affairs Ministry 
completed 
Thursday its 10-day inspection of affiliated organizations 
including Kyonggi provincial government over the 
misappropriation of charity funds. 
  The ministry's inspection was undertaken after the Board of 
Audit and Inspection announced last week that some government 
agencies had misappropriated charity funds donated by the public 
for other purposes. 
  The dismissed governor had used donations for the poor for 
personal expenses and O was found to have forcibly collected 3.9 
billion won from construction firms as charity funds, the 
spokesman said. 

