<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Farmers Polled on Plans After UR Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0703114394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0939 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0703114394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Mar. 7 (YONHAP) -- South Korean farmers have 
grown less enthusiastic about their occupation following the 
conclusion of the Uruguay Round [UR] talks. An opinion poll 
taken by the National Agricultural Cooperative Federation toward 
2,000 farmers at the end of last year showed on Monday that 35.1 
percent of the respondents said they would reduce their farming 
scale to a point where they could obtain food grains of their 
own need only. On the other hand, 45.1 percent replied they 
would continue to engage in farming as now even after the 
Uruguay Round agreement. 
  Those who said they would give up farming altogether 
accounted for 9.2 percent of the total and 10.5 percent said 
they would delegate their farmlands to some ones else. Those who 
said they would abandon farming were mostly those with tiny 
farmlands. Those with relatively large farmland areas said they 
would continue farming. 
  Regarding the issue of whether to allow non-farmers to 
possess farmlands, 54.1 percent favored non-farmers' possession 
in the interests of the buildup of farming competitiveness. But, 
30.7 percent of the questioned said they were against it because 
it runs counter to the traditional principle of "farmlands for 
farmers." 

</TEXT>

