<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Exchange Trade Reportedly `Surging' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0703013694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0108 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0703013694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 7 (YONHAP) -- Foreign exchange trading 
by Korean banks is surging along with the country's developing 
financial structure and wider market opening. 
  Inter-bank foreign exchange transactions grew as much as 136 
percent last year and the role of Korean banks in these deals 
has strengthened greatly, the Finance Ministry said Monday. 
  Foreign exchange transactions were worth 587.8 billion U.S. 
dollars last year, up 39.8 percent from 420.4 billion dollars in 
1992. 
  Trade volume, which was 332.2 billion dollars in 1990, grew 
9.1 percent to 352.5 billion dollars in 1991 and 19.3 percent to 
420.4 billion dollars in 1992, but last year's two-digit rise 
was chiefly attributed to the foreign exchange liberalization 
measures initiated from 1993, Ministry officials said. 
  Daily inter-bank trading averaged 1,172 million dollars last 
year, up 135.8 percent from 497 million dollars a year earlier. 
Daily volume totaled 1,859 million dollars in January and 2,134 
million dollars last month. 
  Spot transactions that stood at 344 million dollars a day in 
1992 expanded 71.5 percent last year to 591 million dollars 
while forward trading surged 279.7 percent to 581 million 
dollars from 153 million dollars. Forward exchange 
transactions that require underlying documents kept growing this 
year to total 1,013 million dollars in January, exceeding 846 
million dollars in spot dealings. 
  Forward trading reached 1,514 million dollars in February, 
compared with 1,082 million dollars in spot deals, with the 
preference for futures reflecting the Korean foreign exchange 
market's further advancement, officials said. 
  In addition, local banks accounted for 63.2 percent of 
inter-bank transactions last year, up from 51.7 percent in 1992. 
  Under a three-phase financial liberalization plan that took 
effect last October, the daily fluctuation band of the 
inter-bank foreign exchange rate was widened and underlying 
document requirements for forward contracts relaxed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-5245 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas044_d_94035" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-044 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bank Reports External Debt Below $10 Billion </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0503015594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0136 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0503015594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 5 (YONHAP) -- South Korea's net 
external debt fell below 10 billion U.S. dollars in 1993 for the 
first time in three years thanks to an increase in the country's 
foreign reserves, the Bank of Korea said Saturday. Net external 
debt, the amount remaining after subtracting foreign reserves 
from total external debt, decreased from 11.1 billion dollars at 
the end of 1992 to 7.98 billion dollars last year. 
  Foreign reserves soared last year as foreigners' investment 
in stocks increased and the current account posted a surplus, 
thereby reducing the nation's net foreign debt. Foreign 
reserves, which include foreign exchange holdings and overseas 
stocks and bonds, reached 36.1 billion dollars at the end of 
last year, up 4.38 billion dollars from the year before. 
  South Korea's balance of current accounts recorded a 
450-million-dollar surplus for the first time in four years, 
while foreigners invested 5.7 billion dollars in stocks here, 
increasing the country's foreign reserves. 
  Meanwhile, total external debt rose 1.26 billion dollars to 
44.08 billion dollars at the end of 1993, from 42.82 billion 
dollars a year earlier. Long-term foreign debt rose by 760 
million dollars from 24.31 billion dollars in 1992 to 25.07 
billion dollars, while short-term debt increased 500 million 
dollars to 19.01 billion dollars. 
  South Korea's net foreign debt decreased to 3.02 billion 
dollars in 1989 when the nation enjoyed a large current account 
surplus, but increased again to 4.85 billion dollars in 1990 and 
11.95 billion dollars a year later. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

