<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Ministers' Letter to Sihanouk on Health </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0603145294 Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 1300 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0603145294 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 1300 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Cambodian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Letter from the Royal Government of Cambodia to His </F>
Majesty Norodom Sihanouk Varaman, King of Cambodia;" dated 3 
March -- read by announcer] 
  [Text] To Your Revered Majesty: 
  After having received Your Majesty's message dated 27 
February 1994, we, the Royal Government of Cambodia [RGC] and 
the public servants and people who are your children throughout 
the country, have been very anxious and terribly concerned over 
your health conditions. 
  Your life is priceless and your initiative is fine to build 
the nation and country toward prosperity in all fields, 
especially to achieve national reconciliation and reinforce 
peace and political stability for the beloved Cambodian 
motherland. 
  On behalf of the RGC, we pledge to pursue your advice and 
are 
determined to sacrifice all our physical and moral efforts to 
following Your Majesty in building the Kingdom of Cambodia 
toward prosperity. 
  Moreover, on behalf of the RGC and the Cambodian people of 
all strata, we pray that the Triple Jewels and all sacred things 
the world over, such as charisma of previous Cambodian kings and 
goddesses protecting the royal parasol, protect Your Majesty. 
May you enjoy the five blessings of Lord Buddha; that is, 
longevity, social prestige, happiness, strength, and 
enlightenment. Especially, may you recover quickly from your 
illness and have a long life so you can return and stay as the 
support for your beloved children and carry on your noble 
mission of leading the Cambodian motherland toward security, 
peace, and social progress. 
  [Dated] Phnom Penh, 3 March 1994 
  [Signed] First Prime Minister Norodom Ranariddh; Second 
Prime Minister Hun Sen 

</TEXT>

