<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   3 KR Leaders, Fighters Reportedly To Surrender </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0603093694 Bangkok THE NATION in English 6 Mar 94 p A2 </F>
<F P=103> BK0603093694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok THE NATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Somchit Sidurongkathum] </F>
  [Text] Phnom Penh -- Three Khmer Rouge [KR] leaders and 
several hundred fighters have agreed to surrender to the 
Cambodian government next month, an informed source said. They 
would turn themselves in as soon as all the felled timber in the 
guerrilla-controlled areas had been dragged out by contractors. 
"It is expected that all logs will be removed by the end of 
March. Then in April they will turn themselves in," he told the 
NATION. "This includes three Khmer Rouge leaders and hundreds of 
their soldiers." 
  He declined to name these "leaders", saying only that Ta 
Mok, 
the one-legged hard-line leader of the guerrilla forces, would 
not be among them. He has reportedly abandoned his bases in 
Anlung Veng Province and moved to new headquarters at Trapeang 
Kul. The source said the three had set conditions for their 
surrender, but declined to give details. He said the U.S. 
government has agreed to provide army uniforms for guerrillas 
who defect to the government forces. 
  Khmer Rouge representatives in Phnom Penh were not available 
for comment. 
  Defense Minister Tea Chamrat and another high-ranking member 
of the government were understood to be due in Bangkok this 
weekend to discuss the surrender. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

