<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials React to U.S.-Japan Trade Dispute </TI></H3>
<H4>   Spokesman on Using Super 301 </H4>
<F P=102> BK0603121294 Bangkok Radio Thailand Network in Thai 0000 GMT 
6 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0603121294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok Radio Thailand Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Thai </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Spokesman of the Prime Minister's Office Aphisit 
Wetchachiwa says Thailand is closely following the U.S. move 
about using Article 301 for trade retaliation. The government 
thinks that international trade atmosphere has largely improved 
following the conclusion of the Uruguay round of trade talks. 
The APEC [Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation] summit meeting was 
also marked by a friendly atmosphere. 
  [Begin recording] [Aphisit] We must follow it closely to 
see whether the move will be applied in general. We must be 
prepared; it is the responsibility of the government that wants 
to see a relaxed atmosphere in international trade. 
  [Unidentified correspondent] Is the U.S. measure meant as 
pressure on this region? 
  [Aphisit] I think it concerns a particular problem. Anyway, 
we cannot remain indifferent but have to follow the developments 
and see whether there is a tendency toward unilateral 
retaliation. As I have said, I believe there will be a 
discussion on this matter at the preparations for the APEC 
meeting. 
  [Correspondent] Will there be any discussion among ourselves 
to prepare for the U.S. move? 
  [Aphisit] The Thai private sector and government are already 
cooperating on that. It's the responsibility of Deputy Prime 
Minister Suphachai Phanitchaphak, in his capacity as head of the 
International Economic Policy Office. There is no problem about 
our preparations to cope with the consequences; we are already 
working together on that. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

