<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Prime Minister Views Investment in Laos </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0503143094 Bangkok PRACHACHAT THURAKIT in Thai 27 Feb-2 
Mar 94 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> BK0503143094 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok PRACHACHAT THURAKIT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Thai </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] According to Deputy Prime Minister Suphachai 
Phanitchaphak, Thailand's image in the eyes of Laos is rather 
negative, resulting in Thai investment in that country to be 
monitored closely by the Lao Government. This has led to a 
reduction in Thai investment in Laos because investors could not 
tolerate Lao Government's witchhunt. The Lao Government's 
suspicions about Thai investment resulted from behavior of 
unscrupulous Thai businessmen. 
  Suphachai said the Thai Government could not gain correct 
understanding of the Lao Government in every issue involving 
Thai investment. The private sector, particularly the chambers 
of commerce in the northeastern provinces, should play a role in 
this matter. The chambers of commerce could join to form a 
"northeast business council" or a committee on Thai-Lao trade to 
screen prospective investors to find good people whose 
investment would not exploit Laos as in the past. The council 
could also set regulations governing Thai businessmen making 
investment in Laos and protect their interests when Laos changes 
its regulations. These frequent changes of Lao regulations have 
always troubled Thai investors. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

