<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police Seize Ammunition Cache Near Burma Border </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0503104194 Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 5 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> BK0503104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BANGKOK POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mae Hong Son -- A special police task force unit 
intercepted a large cache of ammunition just as arms smugglers 
were about to deliver it to customers near the Thai-Burmese 
border yesterday. The cache included 2,500 rounds for an M79 
grenade-launcher and 20,080 rounds for an M60 medium machine 
gun. The seizure happened at about 1 p.m. when 10 policemen were 
patrolling near Ban Mae Suya. They spotted a convoy of 30 
pack-horses being guarded by a group of armed men heading for 
Burmese territory. 
  Because they were outnumbered, police decided to follow the 
gang towards the border until they accidently found a gunny bag 
believed to have fallen from a pack-horse that contained 2,580 
rounds of M79 and M60 ammunition. Police decided to call in more 
reinforcements and fired into the air to stop the convoy but 
they sped away. 
  Police yesterday morning combed the area and found nine 
horses including a dead one, abandoned in the jungle. Each of 
them was found carrying over 2,000 rounds of ammunition. 

</TEXT>

