<F P=101> Australia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Turkey's Cetin on Talks in New Zealand, Australia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0503143694 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1100 
GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0503143694 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Video report by Yasar Kefeli in Australia] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin's visits to New 
Zealand and Australia were based on the aim of further improving 
the existing good relations between Turkey and those countries. 
Cetin stressed that the concrete results of these visits will 
be observed in the near future. 
  At the end of his official visits to New Zealand and 
Australia, Cetin made a statement to Turkish Radio and 
Television. He said that the political will indeed exists to 
develop the relations between these countries. He pointed out 
that his visits were beneficial, and that they showed the 
importance given to Turkey. Cetin also said that additional 
agreements might be signed with those countries. 
  [Begin Cetin recording] Turkey, Australia, and New Zealand 
are members of the western group of the United Nations. New 
Zealand is also a Security Council member. Australia plans to 
be a Security Council member in the future. During my trip, we 
assessed the tasks before the United Nations in the coming 
period and the viewpoint of the UN Security Council regarding 
the developments taking place around Turkey. The issues of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, Nagorno-Karabakh, the developments in the 
Middle East, and the embargo on Iraq are issues that closely 
concern Turkey and that are on the agenda of the United Nations. 
We held a very close exchange of views on these topics. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

