<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Plans Market-Opening Meeting 9 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0503122094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1204 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0503122094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 5 KYODO -- The government of Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa will hold a ministerial meeting 
Wednesday [9 March] to map out voluntary market-opening 
measures, officials said Saturday. 
  The government officials said the decision was made during a 
50- minute meeting between Hosokawa and Chief Cabinet Secretary 
Masayoshi Takemura at Hosokawa's official residence Saturday 
evening. 
  The ministerial session follows a U.S. decision to reinstate 
the Super 301 trade retaliation provision against countries 
deemed to engage in unfair trade practices. 
  U.S. President Bill Clinton took the action after Japan-U.S. 
talks for a new framework for bilateral trade broke down last 
month. 
  The ministerial meeting is timed to coincide with a visit to 
Japan by U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher, who arrives 
on Wednesday for talks the next day with Hosokawa and other 
government leaders on trade and other issues. 
  The officials said the Japanese Government plans to work out 
market-opening measures by the end of March. 
  Japan has been under pressure from the United States and 
Europe to open its markets to reduce its growing current account 
and trade surpluses. 
  The officials said Hosokawa hopes to convey Japan's market- 
opening package to Christopher at their meeting Thursday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

