<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kumano Expects Delay in Market-Opening Measures </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0703071094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0621 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0703071094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 7 KYODO -- Announcement of some of the 
government's market-opening measures could be delayed until the 
next fiscal year, which begins on April 1, a senior Trade 
Ministry official said Monday [7 March]. 
  Vice International Trade and Industry Minister Hideaki 
Kumano 
told a press conference that it is possible that some parts of 
the four-point package, originally planned for release by the 
end of March, will be unveiled toward the July summit of the 
Group of Seven industrial nations in Naples. 
  Kumano was referring to remarks earlier in the day by Chief 
Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura indicating a possible delay 
in the market-opening measures beyond the end of fiscal 1993. 
  Market-opening steps in four areas are being worked out by 
the government following the breakdown in February of the trade 
"framework" talks with the United States. The areas are 
deregulation, import and investment promotion, government 
procurement systems and competition policy. 
  The Naples summit could become a new deadline for some of 
the 
four measures, Kumano said. He declined to comment on which 
sectors might be delayed. 

</TEXT>

