<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Comments on Money Flow to DPRK </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0703005594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0045 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0703005594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 7 (YONHAP) -- Japanese Foreign Minister 
Tsutomu Hata warned of stern countermeasures Sunday if North 
Korea refuses further nuclear inspections or tries to abuse its 
nuclear bargaining card. 
  He said he had heard of various ways that North Koreans in 
Japan were funneling cash into North Korea, but to forcibly cut 
off such channels could raise the issue of human rights 
violations and thus required prudent consideration, he said. 
  Hata described various suspicions regarding Pyongyang's 
nuclear program in an appearance on Fuji TV, including 
speculation that it is manufacturing weapons or has already done 
so and that it possesses the same type of atomic bomb that was 
dropped on Hiroshima by the United States. 
  Japan is ready to make its own assessment of North Korea's 
nuclear development based on inspections conducted by the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and information 
obtained from the United States, South Korea and China, he said. 
  North Korea still has two facilities that haven't been 
inspected, the foreign minister reminded. Depending on its 
future attitude, U.N. sanctions could be imposed, he said. 
  On reports that money sent by Chochongnyon [General 
Association of Korean Residents in Japan], an organization of 
ethnic North Koreans and sympathizers, is being poured into 
Pyongyang's nuclear program, Hata said he had heard figures 
ranging from tens of million Japanese yen to hundreds of million 
yen. 
  The money is reportedly carried personally by people 
returning to North Korea, aboard freight vessels or through Hong 
Kong and China, said Hata. 
  But such funds are being sent by those who were born in 
North 
Korea and think of it as their motherland, he pointed out. 
  Forcibly cutting off the flow, therefore, could raise the 
problem of human rights violations, he said. 

</TEXT>

