<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Phones Congratulations to ROK Leader </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0703143994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1430 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0703143994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 7 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa told South Korean President Kim Yong-sam on Monday [7 
March] he wants to resolve Japan's trade dispute with the United 
States, government officials said. Hosokawa made the comment 
during a phone call to Kim in which he congratulated him over 
the passage of political reform legislation in the South Korean 
legislature. 
  Hosokawa reportedly said he "must find a clue to solve" 
Japan's trade surplus with the United States. 
  Kim told Hosokawa he "hopes trade friction with the U.S. can 
be solved in a beneficial way." 
  The prime minister paid tribute to Kim's leadership and zeal 
in achieving political reform. 
  Kim said that "advance is not possible without political 
reform." 
  "The South Korean community will become stable for the first 
time as a result of clean elections," Kim reportedly said. 

</TEXT>

