<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo To Offer Cambodia Fresh Grant Assistance </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0303124394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1054 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303124394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 3 KYODO -- Japan will offer Cambodia 
some 9 billion yen in grant assistance for fiscal 1994, which 
begins April 1, government sources said Thursday [3 March]. The 
sources said the decision will be formally announced at a 
two-day international conference on Cambodia to be held in Tokyo 
from March 10. 
  Japan allocated 8.4 billion yen in grant assistance to 
Cambodia in the current fiscal year ending March 31. The fresh 
funds will go toward such projects as rehabilitation of 
Cambodia's national route 6, restoration of a power plant in 
Phnom Penh and improvement of water supply and drainage in the 
capital. 
  Tokyo has invited representatives of 31 countries, the 
European Union and 12 international organizations to attend the 
second meeting of the International Committee on Reconstruction 
of Cambodia. 
  Japan pledged in 1992 to provide between 150 and 200 million 
dollars to Cambodia over a three-year period covering fiscal 
1992 to 1994. Foreign Ministry officials said Japan has since 
disbursed around 190 million dollars, making it the largest 
donor nation. 

</TEXT>

