<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Political Reform Package Amendments Become Law </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0403040094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0328 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0403040094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 4 KYODO -- The House of Councillors on 
Friday [4 March] made into law political reform package 
amendments which feature changes in the House of 
Representatives' election system and revised regulations on 
corporate donations to political fund-raising organizations. 
The upper house approved the amendments following passage by 
the lower house Tuesday. 
  Under the amendments, 300 seats will be allocated for 
single-seat constituencies and 200 by proportional 
representation based on the popular vote in 11 electoral units. 
Currently, 511 lower house members are elected from multiseat 
constituencies. 
  The complete reform package will be enforced after enactment 
of another law identifying the locations of the 300 single-seat 
constituencies. 
  Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura has said the 
coalition government wants to submit a bill on the 
constituencies' locations to the current Diet session ending 
June 29. But the presentation may be delayed to autumn if 
legislators insist their opinions be reflected on the locations. 
  The original government-sponsored package called for 274 
single-seat districts and 226 seats allotted by proportional 
representation on a nationwide basis. The original package 
banned corporate donations to politicians and their fund-raising 
organizations, but the revised bills will allow firms to donate 
up to 500,000 yen per year during the next five years as a 
temporary provision. 
  The original package was passed on January 29 at an 
extraordinary Diet session shortly after Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa and opposition Liberal Democratic Party President Yohei 
Kono agreed that the amendments and date of enforcement would be 
discussed during the current ordinary session. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-5292 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas044_a_94018" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-044 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 March 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Faces Lawsuit on Reform Bill Compromise </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0603100894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0955 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0603100894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Miyazaki, March 6 KYODO -- A former Fair Trade 
Commission (FTC) inspector intends to file a lawsuit Monday [7 
March] against Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa for allegedly 
violating the Constitution through a compromise over political 
reform bills in January. 
  The former FTC official, Taro Kayashima, 68, will file the 
suit at the Miyazaki district court against Hosokawa, opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) President Yohei Kono and speaker 
of the House of Representatives Takako Doi. 
  Kayashima is seeking a total of 3 million yen from the three 
and the government as compensation for the damage which he said 
was inflicted by the compromise via a backdoor deal. 
  The government-proposed political reform bills were 
initially 
rejected in the House of Councillors and the likelihood of 
enactment became slim because of disagreement over compromise 
between representatives of the two Diet chambers. 
  Doi, however, proposed her own conciliatory plan to Hosokawa 
and Kono, and the two men took advantage of the proposal as a 
chance to reach an accord in a backroom meeting. 
  Kayashima claims the actions taken by Doi, Hosokawa and Kono 
violated the Constitution. 
  The plaintiff alleges that Hosokawa, as leader of the 
government, intervened in deliberations in the conference 
committee of both houses. 
  Hosokawa allegedly violated separation of the 
administrative, 
legislature and judicial branches of the government, thus 
damaging trust in parliamentary democracy, Kayashima said. 
  In addition, Kayashima claims infringement on his liberty to 
support a political party because the political reform bills 
guarantee designated parties to receive public financial 
assistance paid through taxes. 
  The upper house on Friday made into law political reform 
package amendments which feature changes in the lower house's 
election system and revised regulations on corporate donations 
to political fund-raising organizations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

