<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Advisory Panel To Upgrade Energy Demand Outlook </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203132894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1238 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0203132894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 2 KYODO -- A government advisory panel 
said Wednesday [2 March] it will revise its long-term domestic 
energy demand-supply outlook because the nation's energy 
consumption is growing at a faster pace than the panel 
previously projected. The advisory committee for energy, a 
panel of the Ministry of International Trade and Industry, said 
the existing projection, worked out in June 1990, will be 
replaced in May by new forecasts for 2000 and 2010. 
  The group said energy consumption has been expanding at a 
faster pace than it projected while supply growth is expected to 
remain slow. The panel said the prospect for energy supply is 
dim because the development of alternate energy sources has 
become stagnant and the construction of new nuclear power plants 
has been hampered due to difficulty in finding construction 
sites. 
  The current outlook puts an annual average increase of 
Japan's energy consumption at 1.6 percent toward the year 2000. 
The panel said domestic consumption, which bloated during the 
"bubble economy," continued to rise at an average rate of over 3 
percent despite the recession. 
  It also noted that Japan's dependence on crude oil has not 
declined as expected because of low oil prices. 
  The committee said the new outlook will incorporate a plan 
to 
promote the use of alternate energy sources which discharge 
lower levels of carbon dioxide than fossil fuels to meet the 
government-set goal for per-capita CO2 emissions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

