<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Steel Exports Increase 20.6 Percent in Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0303100394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0804 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303100394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 3 KYODO -- Japan's steel exports in 
January rose 20.6 percent from a year earlier to 1,495,000 tons, 
an industry association reported Thursday [3 March]. The 
exports, however, fell 33.1 percent from the previous month, the 
Japan Iron and Steel Federation said. 
  January exports were valued at 961.66 million dollars, up 
7.1 
percent from a year earlier, or 107.6 billion yen, down 4.0 
percent. The yen value posted the sixth consecutive year-on-year 
fall. 
  Exports to South Korea surged 186.8 percent to 258,000 tons, 
due to increased pig iron exports, surpassing those to China. 
  Exports to China totaled 232,000 tons, up 4.2 percent, 
Taiwan 
192,000 tons, up 17.2 percent, and the United States 164,000 
tons, up 43.9 percent. 
  The federation said imports of ordinary steel in January 
fell 
5.1 percent from a year earlier to 470,000 tons for the fifth 
consecutive year-on-year decline. 

</TEXT>

