<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Industry To Continue Muse System for HDTV </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0303090894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0720 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0303090894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 3 KYODO -- Japan's electronics 
industry leader said Thursday [3 March] it will continue using 
the muse system for its high-definition television (HDTV) system 
for the 21st century. 
  Tadahiro Sekimoto, chairman of the Electronic Industries 
Association of Japan, said, "Japan's muse system has been 
completed and we have no idea of giving up the HDTV system." 
  Sekimoto's comment was in response to the recent widespread 
misunderstanding that the muse system may be replaced by the 
"MPEG" system of the United States. The view was triggered by a 
posts ministry official's remark in February discussing the 
digital and analog formats for the future HDTV system in Japan. 
  "Analog-or-digital discussion is nonsense. That is based on 
lack of technological knowledge. In the core part of the muse, 
signals are digitally processed and the data can be output 
digitally," Sekimoto said. 
  Sekimoto, also president of NEC Corp., made the remarks at a 
press conference. 
  Even in an era of multimedia, which need to digitally 
operate 
data via optical networks, the muse system will be fully 
applicable to the next generation high-tech world, Sekimoto said. 
  For instance, Japanese manufacturers have already developed 
a 
digital videocassette tape recorder for the muse-HDTV set, 
Sekimoto said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

