<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman on `Positive' U.S. Property Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0203092094 Hanoi VNA in English 0914 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK0203092094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi VNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hanoi, March 2 (AFP) -- The first round of 
discussions between Vietnam and the United States on recovering 
seized property at the end of the Vietnam War ended here "with 
positive results," the foreign ministry said Wednesday. 
  "There are still some concrete problems that will be 
discussed at the next meeting at the working level," a foreign 
ministry spokesman told AFP without specifying when or where the 
next round of discussions would take place. 
  U.S. State Department officials refused to comment on the 
talks. 
  The bilateral meeting, the first since Washington lifted an 
economic embargo on Vietnam on February 4, lasted two days and 
brought together State Department, Treasury and Justice 
Department officials with their Vietnamese counterparts. 
  Claims by the two sides are estimated to total more than 500 
million dollars in assets seized or frozen following the fall of 
Saigon in 1975. 
  The opening of reciprocal representative offices in Hanoi 
and 
Washington, proposed by US President Bill Clinton, has already 
been accepted in principle by Vietnam. 
  U.S. delegation leader, James Hall, at his own request 
visited sites of searches for American servicemen missing in 
action, said the Vietnamese spokesman. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

