<H3> <TI>   Power Line Project `Essentially' Complete </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0603090094 Hanoi VNA in English 0523 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK0603090094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi VNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hanoi VNA March 6 -- Tenders for [words indistinct] 
equipment, materials, and services for the But Son cement 
project were invited here on March 1. 
  The But Son cement plant, with a capacity of 1.4 tonnes per 
year, was constructed in Thanh On Commune (Kim Bang District, 
Nam Ha Province). After the Vietnam Cement Corporation invited 
tender, six companies from Denmark, Japan, South Korea, France, 
and Germany entered bids. The companies include : CLE and 
Mkrubeni, KHD Humboldt and Cosaliberman, Hyundai, Krupp Polysius 
and Itochu, F.L Smith and Mitsui, UBE and Nissho Iwai. The 
lowest tender was USD 96.5 million, and the highest one was USD 
187.2 million. 
  A 12-member bidding council was set up with Mr. Tran Van 
Huynh, deputy minister of construction, as its head. The cement 
consulting investment and development company was appointed by 
the contractor as the bid's advisor. 
  The construction of the 500 kv Trans-viet power line project 
has essentially been completed. 
  Power poles in 3,436 building sites of the whole network 
from 
Hoa Binh to Phu Lam were erected, 1,487 km of parallel 
conductive line and safety line had been completely installed by 
February 25, according to information from the 500 kv Trans-Viet 
power line project's managing board. 

</TEXT>

