<H3> <TI>   Customs Sector Conference Sets Revenue Target </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0403045994 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network in Vietnamese 
1100 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0403045994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Vietnamese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Customs General Department held a conference 
from 1-3 March to discuss measures to fulfill its 1994 duties 
and orientations for building up the customs sector before 2000. 
Deputy Prime Minister Phan Van Khai addressed the conference. 
  This year the customs sector was assigned by the state to 
collect 8,500 billion dong in import-export taxes. At the 
conference, the officials discussed various measures to 
implement state regulations and orders on renovating economic 
thinking in line with the party's open door policy; initiating 
and submitting to the government new regulations and policies 
that respond to the needs of the new situation; reforming 
supervision mechanisms to ensure convenience for local residents 
and foreign guests in traveling in and out of the country; 
maintaining a smooth flow of trade; and suppressing smuggling 
and tax evasion. 
  The sector will strive to fight corruption, and expel and 
bring to trial those degenerate cadres and officials. The 
customs offices will also pay more attention in improving 
statistical work, upgrading facilities so that they can help the 
government with effective macroeconomic management. 

</TEXT>

