<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   BOJ Source Welcomes U.S. Jobless Rate Decline </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0403143494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1422 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0403143494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 4 KYODO -- A Bank of Japan [BOJ] 
source on Friday [4 March] welcomed the decline in the U.S. 
jobless rate for February as good for bilateral relations and 
the global economy as well. "This could be a factor which 
softens the recent stiff bilateral relations (between Japan and 
the United States), and it's a stabilizing factor for the world 
economy," the source said. 
  The labor department reported the U.S. jobless rate fell to 
6.5 percent in February from 6.7 percent in January, with 
nonfarm payrolls growing by 217,000. 
  The central bank source said the February increase in 
nonfarm 
payrolls was larger than expected despite cold weather for that 
month. 
  "This points to a recovery of the U.S. economy and an 
increase in competitiveness in the U.S. Manufacturing sector," 
he said. He did not elaborate. 

</TEXT>

