<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Comments on Envoy Exchange </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0503023894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0228 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0503023894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 5 (YONHAP) -- South Korea brushed aside 
the communist North's claim Saturday [day as received] that an 
inter- Korean envoy exchange is not required for a third round 
of Pyongyang-Washington high-level talks. 
  "This was something we expected (North Korea to do)," Chang 
Chae-yong, director-general of American Affairs at the Foreign 
Ministry, said in reaction. 
  "We don't feel the need to say anything about it. We have to 
wait and see," Chang said. 
  North Korean first Vice Foreign Minister Kang Sok-chu said 
the envoy exchange is not part of the agreed preconditions for 
the high-level talks, slated for March 21 in Geneva. 
  Seoul, Pyongyang and Washington announced a set of joint 
measures this week after North Korea allowed entry by a team of 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) inspectors. But 
Washington made a separate announcement that while the date for 
the high-level negotiations has been set, successful IAEA 
inspections and an inter-Korean presidential envoy exchange are 
two prerequisites. 
  "North Korea agreed that Washington would make this separate 
announcement," Chang said. 

</TEXT>

