<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, March 5 (KCNA) -- U.S. Secretary of 
State Christopher finally confirmed that the demand for the 
repeal of the "National Security Law" [NSL] in South Korea is 
not a personal opinion but an official stand of the United 
States, the Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation (MBC) of South Korea 
reported. 
  Answering a question put by the MBC on the evening of March 
3, he made it clear that, although the repeal of the 
controversial "National Security Law" of South Korea was a 
sensitive matter, the U.S. Government would persuade South 
Korea to repeal it. 
  He added that this demand of the United States to South 
Korea 
was motivated by its fear that the "National Security Law" might 
be abused. 
  This final confirmation of the U.S. State secretary came 
shortly after the South Korean puppet Foreign Ministry announced 
on March 3 that the remarks of U.S. Deputy Assistant Secretary 
of State Hubbard urging the repeal of the "National Security 
Law" in South Korea had "turned out" to be an "expression of 
his personal hope", not the official position of the United 
States. 

