<F P=101> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Comments on Peacekeepers for West Bank </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0703072194 Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA in English 0623 GMT 7 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0703072194 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kuala Lumpur, March 7 (OANA/BERNAMA) -- Malaysia has 
not received any official proposal from the United Nations (UN) 
to station peacekeepers in the West Bank to protect 
Palestinians. Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said if the 
UN decided to send peacekeeping troops to the West Bank, 
Malaysia would consider participating since it already had such 
commitments in other countries. Until now, the government has 
not received any official proposal from the UN and if there is 
any it will be channelled through the UN office, he told 
reporters in the northern Penang state Sunday. 
  However, he said, the decision to send Malaysian soldiers to 
serve under the UN would be up to Defence Minister Najib Razak 
and the cabinet. 

</TEXT>

