<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economic Leaders on U.S. Decision on Super 301 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0503100994 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 5 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 5 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0503100994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The United States has decided to reinstate the Super 
301 provision of the Omnibus Trade and Competitiveness Act 
(which identifies nations engaging in unfair trade practices and 
imposes sanctions on them). Economic leaders have voiced their 
strong dissatisfaction. 
  Gaishi Hiraiwa, chairman of the Federation of Economic 
Organizations of Japan; Kosaku Inaba, chairman of the Japan 
Chamber of Commerce and Industry; and Osamu Uno, chairman of the 
Kansai Economic Federation each said: "This apparently runs 
counter to the spirit of GATT." 
  Masaru Hayami, chairman of Japan Association of Corporate 
Executives, said: "This runs counter to the spirit of free 
trade." 
  Takeshi Nagano, president of the Japan Federation of 
Employers' Association, said the leaders also expressed concern 
that such action "will be dangerous to relations between Japan 
and the United States," and noted the need to quickly improve 
relations between the two. 
  As far as countermeasures are concerned, Mr. Hiraiwa said 
some economic leaders hoped the United States "will take action 
cool-headedly. 
  Mr. Nagano said others stressed the need for Japan to work 
out concrete measures to reduce its trade surplus, saying: 
"Japan should throw the ball back to the United States soon." 
  Mr. Hiraiwa stressed: "Japan needs to expand domestic demand 
and implement clear and quick action on deregulation and 
promoting market opening." 
  Mr. Hayami said: "Japan's efforts must address two issues: 
First reducing the current account surplus, second narrowing the 
disparity between domestic and overseas prices." He called on 
the government to promote such measures as a target for reducing 
the current account surplus which is linked to the gross 
domestic product (GDP). 
  There was also the feeling that private companies should try 
to improve relations with the United States. 
  Mr. Inaba said one of the suggestions was for "Japan and the 
United States to hold industry-to-industry consultations in 
controversial areas of trade. 
  Mr. Hayami said others saw the need for the private sector 
to 
make additional efforts to voluntarily increase imports through 
international procurement and improved distribution and 
transaction practices." 
  Mr. Uno said that leaders were critical, however, of 
attempts 
to set numerical targets in the microeconomy, saying: "Methods 
like managed trade should be eliminated." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

