<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Favors Macroeconomic Numerical Targets </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0503121494 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 4 Mar 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0503121494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 4 March Evening Edition] </F>
  [Text] At a news conference following a cabinet meeting on 
4 March, Transport Minister Shigeru Ito said: "I am opposed to 
setting microeconomic numerical targets, which could lead to 
managed trade. However, setting macroeconomic numerical targets 
is acceptable." 
  He then proposed that as a specific numerical target, the 
government set itself the task of reducing Japan's current 
account surplus to about 2.5 percent of gross domestic product 
(the government proposes a figure of 2.8 percent in its economic 
outlook for fiscal 1994). 
  At the same news conference, Manae Kubota, director general 
of the Economic Planning Agency, touched on the government's 
430-trillion yen public investment plan, saying: "The 
government should consider reviewing the plan, including 
increasing that amount." 
  Her comments were a call for Japan to reduce its surplus by 
strengthening domestic demand. 

</TEXT>

