<H3> <TI>   Cellular Phone Negotiations `Nearing' Finish </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0503075994 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 4 Mar 
Evening Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0503075994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At a news conference following a cabinet meeting on 
4 March, Posts and Telecommunications Minister Takenori Kanzaki 
said negotiations on the cellular phone issue -- one of the 
major areas of trade dispute between Japan and the United States 
-- could be nearing a conclusion. 
  He said: "Japanese and U.S. companies are talking to each 
other actively and in depth; I would like to think we may soon 
get some results from these talks." 
  He was asked if he thought a settlement would be possible by 
17 March, the date on which the United States says it will 
announce a list of sanctions measures against Japan. 
  He said: "I don't know," but ended on a note of cautious 
optimism by saying the 17 March deadline could well prove to be 
"a turning point" in the negotiations. 

</TEXT>

